  "local_port": 34184,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Last year my score for CAT was around 40 percentile. What should I do to score > 90  percentile this year?",
  "response": "To significantly improve your CAT score from the 40th percentile to above the 90th percentile, you'll need a structured and dedicated approach to your preparation. Here\u2019s a step-by-step plan to help you achieve this goal:\n\n### 1. **Understand the Exam Structure**\n   - **CAT** consists of three sections: Verbal Ability and Reading Comprehension (VARC), Data Interpretation and Logical Reasoning (DILR), and Quantitative Ability (QA).\n   - Each section has a different weightage and requires a different set of skills.\n\n### 2. **Assess Your Current Level**\n   - Start by taking a full-length mock test to understand your current strengths and weaknesses in each section.\n   - Analyze your performance to identify areas where you need the most improvement.\n\n### 3. **Set a Study Schedule**\n   - Allocate at least 3-4 hours daily for CAT preparation.\n   - Plan your week to cover all sections and include time for revision and mock tests.\n\n### 4. **Focus on Weak Areas**\n   - **VARC**: Improve your reading speed and comprehension. Practice reading different genres and summarize articles. Work on vocabulary by learning new words daily.\n   - **DILR**: Practice various types of puzzles and data sets. Understand different approaches to solve these problems efficiently.\n   - **QA**: Strengthen your fundamentals in algebra, geometry, number systems, and arithmetic. Solve a variety of problems to build speed and accuracy.\n\n### 5. **Use Quality Study Material**\n   - Invest in good preparation books like Arun Sharma\u2019s \"How to Prepare for Quantitative Aptitude for CAT\" and \"How to Prepare for Verbal Ability and Reading Comprehension for CAT,\" and Nishit Sinha\u2019s \"Logical Reasoning and Data Interpretation for CAT.\"\n   - Supplement with online resources like 2IIM, Testbook, or TIME.\n\n### 6. **Mock Tests and Analysis**\n   - Take regular mock tests (at least one every week) to track your progress.\n   - After each test, analyze your performance to understand your mistakes and work on them.\n   - Focus on improving your speed and accuracy.\n\n### 7. **Time Management**\n   - During mock tests, practice time allocation across sections. Aim to finish each section within the stipulated time.\n   - Learn to quickly decide when to move on from a question if it's taking too long.\n\n### 8. **Stay Updated**\n   - Keep up with current affairs, especially for the VARC section. Reading newspapers and magazines can help.\n   - Stay aware of any changes in the CAT exam pattern or syllabus.\n\n### 9. **Health and Well-being**\n   - Ensure you get enough sleep and maintain a healthy diet.\n   - Regular exercise can help improve concentration and reduce stress.\n\n### 10. **Seek Guidance**\n   - Consider joining a coaching class if you feel you need structured guidance.\n   - Online forums and study groups can also be helpful for discussions and clarifications.\n\n### 11. **Final Month Strategy**\n   - In the last month before the exam, focus on revision and taking full-length mock tests.\n   - Work on your weaker areas but do not ignore your strengths.\n   - Keep practicing under timed conditions to build stamina for the actual exam.\n\n### 12. **Exam Day Preparation**\n   - Be well-rested and have a good breakfast on the exam day.\n   - Arrive early at the exam center to avoid any last-minute stress.\n\nBy following this structured approach, you can significantly improve your performance and increase your chances of scoring above the 90th percentile in CAT. Good luck with your preparation!",
